{{coord|35|47|23.86|N|139|33|36.81|E|display=title}} {{Infobox religious building | name = Heirin-ji | native_name = 金鳳山平林寺 | image = Heirinjigate.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Front gate at Heirinji | map_type = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | location = 3-1-1 Nobidome, Niiza-shi, Saitama-ken | coordinates = | religious_affiliation = [[Rinzai]] | deity = [[Gautama Buddha|Shaka Nyorai]] | country = Japan | functional_status = | website = {{official|http://www.heirinji.or.jp/index.html}} {{ja icon}} | founded_by = Sekishitsu Zenkyū | year_completed = 1375 }} {{nihongo|'''Heirin-ji'''|平林寺}} is a [[Rinzai]] temple of the [[Myoshin-ji]] branch located in [[Niiza, Saitama|Niiza city]], [[Saitama prefecture]], [[Japan]], a city just outside [[Tokyo]].
==History== The temple was founded in [[Iwatsuki, Saitama]] in 1375 by Sekishitsu Zenkyū, who had served as the Abbot of [[Engaku-ji]], [[Tenryū-ji]] and [[Shōfuku-ji (Fukuoka)|Shōfuku-ji]].<ref>http://kotobank.jp/word/石室善玖</ref> During this period the original temple was destroyed in 1590 during an attack on [[Iwatsuki Castle]] by [[Toyotomi Hideyoshi]].
It was rebuilt in 1603 by [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]] and moved to Niiza city sixty years later. The temple grounds are situated in a [[forest]]ed area and is considered to be a national monument. Heirin-ji differs from other temples in the Tokyo area by having no temple markets nor public festivals held at the temple.
The temple remains a training temple for monks, who can often be seen working in the grounds. The grounds of the temple preserve a stretch of the [[Musashino Terrace|Musashino]] woodlands. Animals such as [[raccoon dog]]s that are now not often seen in the city are found around the temple. The grounds also provide a roost for a large murder of [[Jungle Crow|Japanese crows]]. The gardens are notable for the [[maple tree]]s in autumn and the ''[[ume]]'' blossoms in early spring. The bell, with the ''ume'' blossom, was the inspiration for one of [[Toshi Yoshida]]'s wood block prints.<ref>Watanabe, 39</ref><ref>McDonagh</ref>
== See also == * For an explanation of terms concerning Japanese Buddhism, Japanese Buddhist art, and Japanese Buddhist temple architecture, see the [[Glossary of Japanese Buddhism]].
