{{Sangam literature}}
'''Iraiyanar''' ([[Tamil language|Tamil]]: இறையனார்), literally meaning "the Lord" and also a common name of [[Shiva]], was a legendary poet of the [[Sangam period]] who is believed to have composed verse 2 of [[Kurunthogai]].<ref name="SangaIlakkiyam_2">{{cite book | last = Kowmareeshwari (Ed.) | first = S. | author-link = | title = Kurunthogai, Paripaadal, Kalitthogai | publisher = Saradha Pathippagam | series = Sanga Ilakkiyam | volume = 2 | edition = 1 | date = August 2012 | location = Chennai | pages = | language = Tamil | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref> He was believed to be the incarnation of [[Lord Shiva]] of the [[Madurai Meenakshi temple|temple]] at [[Madurai]], known as 'Aalavaai Sokkar' or 'Sokkanathar'.<ref name="SangaIlakkiyam_2"/> Verse 3 of the [[Tiruvalluva Maalai]], praising [[Valluvar]], is also attributed to him.<ref>{{cite book | last = Vedanayagam | first = Rama | author-link = | title =Tiruvalluva Maalai: Moolamum Eliya Urai Vilakkamum | publisher = Manimekalai Prasuram | series = | volume = | edition = 1 | date = 2017 | location = Chennai | pages =44–45 | language = Tamil | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>
==Legend== Iraiyanar appears in the ''Tiruvilaiyadal Puranam'', where he confronts poet Nakkeerar.{{citation required|date=February 2018}} He is also said to have given the work [[Iraiyanar Akapporul]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Zvelebil|1973a|pp=112–113}}</ref>
